The '''Bravio delle botti''' (''Bravio of the barrels)'' is an annual race held in the Italian town of [[Montepulciano]] since 1974, replacing an equivalent horserace dating back to 1373. Teams of two runners (spingitori) representing the eight districts of the town ([[contrade]]) compete to be the first to roll an 80&nbsp;kg [[Oak (wine)|wine barrel]] through the streets of the historic centre from the ''Colonna del Marzocco'' to the finish on the ''Piazza Grande,'' the cathedral square. The total distance is approximately 1800m and is uphill for nearly the entire course. As the streets are narrow and the barrels cumbersome to manoeuvre, collisions are frequent.
The word "bravio" derives from the Latin ''Bravium'' meaning "to be won". It refers to the prize given to the winning Contrada - a painted cloth bearing the image of the patron saint of the city.
{{External media|video1 = [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=vEtITJCfumI Official video of the 2012 race]|video2 = [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=_epNWZ40wI8 Official video of the 2014 race]}}
The Contrade, and their colours, are:<ref>{{Cite web|title = Contrade {{!}} Bravio delle Botti di Montepulciano|url = http://www.braviodellebotti.com/contrade/|website = www.braviodellebotti.com|accessdate = 2015-08-31}}</ref> * ''Cagnano'': green and blue * ''Collazzi'': yellow and green * ''Le Coste'': yellow and blue * Gracciano: green and black * ''Poggiolo'': white and blue * ''San Donato:'' white and red * ''Talosa'': yellow and red * ''Voltaia'': red and black Related festivities are held throughout the week of the Bravio including processions, religious blessing, practice runs, and parties hosted at each of the team headquarters.
