{{short description|1769 jubilee celebrating William Shakespeare in Stratford-upon-Avon}}
[[File:Bodleian Libraries, Ticket of Stratford, 6 + 7 Sept 1769, announcing the Shakespeare Jubilee Festival.jpg|thumb|Part of a ticket announcing the Shakespeare Jubilee ([[Bodleian Libraries]], Oxford)]]

The '''Shakespeare Jubilee''' was staged in [[Stratford-upon-Avon]] between 6 and 8 September 1769.{{sfn|Cunningham|2008|p=106}} The jubilee was organised by the [[actor]] and [[theatre manager]] [[David Garrick]] to celebrate the Jubilee of the birth of [[William Shakespeare]]. It had a major impact on the rising tide of [[bardolatry]] that led to Shakespeare's becoming established as the English [[national poet]]. [[Thomas Arne]] composed the song ''[[Soft Flowing Avon]]'' for the Jubilee.

Stratford was at the time a town with around 2,200 inhabitants.{{sfn|Pierce|2005|p=4}} Garrick, Britain's most famous Shakespearean actor and most influential theatre owner-manager, had the idea for the Jubilee when he was approached by the town's leaders who wanted him to fund a statue of Shakespeare to stand in the Town Hall. Garrick planned a major celebration with major figures from London's cultural, political and economic world attending. He oversaw the construction of a large [[Rotunda (architecture)|rotunda]], based on that in [[Ranelagh Gardens]] in London, which could hold 1,000 spectators.{{sfn|Pierce|2005|pp=4–5}} "It is difficult to exaggerate how much space in the papers in the weeks and months beforehand was devoted to discussion of the Jubilee, announcing details of the program, advertising various accoutrements, reporting progress, speculating about its form, and attacking it."{{sfn|Tankard|2014|p=18}}

The Jubilee opened on 6 September with the firing of thirty [[cannons]] and the ringing of [[church bells]].{{sfn|Deelman|1964|p=175}} Various events were held to commemorate Shakespeare's life. It drew in many people from fashionable society, or who were involved in the London theatre. There were seven hundred people at the dinner on the first day.{{sfn|Deelman|1964|p=177}} On the second day bad weather began to disrupt the proceedings and flooded parts of the Rotunda when the banks of the [[River Avon (Warwickshire)|River Avon]] broke. The highlights of the second day were the unveiling of the new statue at the Town Hall and a [[Masquerade ball|masquerade]] held in the evening.{{sfn|Pierce|2005|pp=8–9}} Another notable event from the second day of the Jubilee was a speech by Garrick thanking the [[Shakespeare Ladies Club]] for making Shakespeare popular again and for their contribution to the memorial statue of Shakespeare in [[Poets' Corner]] in [[Westminster Abbey]].{{sfn|Stochholm|1964|p=91}}{{sfn|Dobson|1992|p=148}} The third day was to have seen a grand Shakespeare [[Procession|Pageant]] but the heavy rain forced this to be cancelled. Garrick later staged [[The Jubilee|the Pageant]] in the [[Theatre Royal, Drury Lane|Drury Lane Theatre]] where it was a success, running for ninety performances.{{sfn|Pierce|2005|pp=9–10}} 

It was the first jubilee celebration of the life of Shakespeare, although it was held more than five years after the bicentenary of his birth in April 1564.{{sfn|Pierce|2005|p=4}} In spite of the impact it had on the rising popularity of Shakespeare and his works, none of his plays were performed during the Jubilee.{{sfn|Pierce|2005|p=9}}

